Stop to "UFL" Demanded in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 30 (KCNA) -- The Anti-U.S. Women's Society of south Korea reportedly issued a statement titled "The south Korean and U.S. governments, stop at once UFL-05" on August 23.
 The statement said that the "Ulji Focus Lens-05" joint military exercises are lashing the Koreans desirous of reunification into fury as they are under way at a time when the desire of all the fellow countrymen for reunification is growing stronger than ever before. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Such undisguised saber-rattling against the north goes to clearly prove that the U.S. talk about a "peaceful solution to the nuclear issue" is no more than hypocrisy, the statement said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Voicing strong opposition to the joint military exercises hamstringing the reunification movement of the nation, the statement urged the United States not to threaten the Koreans by force of arms but sincerely pursue a dialogue with the north.

Reception Hosted by Chinese Ambassador 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 30 (KCNA) -- Chinese Ambassador to the DPRK Wu Donghe gave a reception at the embassy Monday evening on the occasion of the 60th anniversary of the victory in the anti-Japanese war.
 Speaking at the reception, Wu Donghe said September 3 is the day marking the 60th anniversary of the victory of the Chinese people in the anti-Japanese war. On August 15 sixty years ago Japan proclaimed an unconditional surrender, he said.
 Noting that the Chinese and Korean peoples forged close and deep friendly relations in blood while fighting shoulder to shoulder against the Japanese aggressors, he said: The Korean revolutionaries headed by President Kim Il Sung, the great leader of the Korean people, wrote an epic of bloody struggle against the Japanese aggressors in the Chinese land jointly with the Chinese comrades. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the steadfast strategic policy of the Chinese party and government to steadily consolidate the friendly and cooperative relations between China and the DPRK, he stated, adding: We, together with the Korean comrades, will constantly bring these relations up to a higher stage as required by the new century, following the policy of "inheriting tradition, facing the future, continuing good neighborliness and enhancing cooperation" and thus bring happiness to the peoples of the two countries and defend the regional and global peace, stability and development.
 DPRK Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun, speaking next, said the victory in the anti-Japanese war was a historic event which opened the way of building a new society in the two countries and laid solid foundations for the prosperity of the countries and nations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK-China friendship with a long history and tradition has entered a road of new development under the deep care of leader Kim Jong Il and General Secretary Hu Jintao, he noted, and referred to the brisk mutual visits of high-level delegations of the two countries and successful furnace firing ceremony at the Taean Friendship Glass Factory, a symbol of DPRK-China friendship. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We are rejoiced as over our own over the successful progress of all things in our fraternal neighboring country and sincerely wish the Chinese people greater results in the work to build a comprehensively well-off society and achieve the complete reunification of the country under the leadership of the Communist Party of China with Hu Jintao as its general secretary, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the reception on invitation were President Kim Yong Nam and Vice-President Yang Hyong Sop of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly of the DPRK, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Members of the Chinese embassy were on hand.

Abolition of Outdated Cold War Structure Urged 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 30 (KCNA) - The commander of the U.S.-south Korea Combined Forces, when interviewed by a newspaper recently, faulted and decried the DPRK's efforts to establish a new peace-keeping mechanism on the Korean Peninsula and cried out for maintaining  the state of armistice. 
 In this regard Rodong Sinmun Tuesday says in a signed commentary:
 His remarks asserting the preservation of the Korean armistice agreement fully reflect the U.S. administration's policy toward the DPRK aimed at justifying its military presence in south Korea and its policy of aggression against the DPRK and using the Korean Peninsula as a ground for confrontation in a new Cold War in the 21st century and a centre for carrying out its strategy to invade Asia. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The United States is keen to maintain the present state of armistice on the Korean Peninsula in a bid to use it as an effective way and leverage for achieving its criminal military strategic objective. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Today the Korean Peninsula has become a very dangerous hotspot as it is the area where the situation remains tensest in the world and a war may break out any moment. 
 The U.S. must be aware that the continued state of unstable armistice on the peninsula is bound to lead to an unpredictable dangerous phase.
 The replacement of the outdated armistice mechanism by a peace- keeping one is essential for terminating all hostile relations between the DPRK and the U.S. including the nuclear stand-off. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. persistently works hard to maintain the present state of armistice, dead-set against the DPRK's proposal and efforts for replacing the armistice mechanism by a peace-keeping one, it will further strain the DPRK-U.S. hostile relations and make it impossible to deter the situation on the Korean Peninsula from leading to the brink of war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Whether the armistice mechanism is replaced by a peace-keeping one or not is a crucial issue deciding war or peace. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the United States is truly willing to settle the hostile relations between the DPRK and U.S. including the nuclear stand-off, it should make a bold decision to replace the present state of armistice, the leftover of the Cold War in the last century, by a new peace-keeping mechanism and thus fulfill its commitment as the party directly responsible for settling the Korean issue.

Kim Yong Nam Meets South Koreans and Overseas Koreans 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 30 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, Tuesday met and conversed with Choe Mun Sun, president of the MBC of south Korea, and his party and Ri Hak Yu, secretary general of the Society to Remember Rev. Son Jong Do, and his entourage, in a compatriotic atmosphere at the Mansudae Assembly Hall. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand were officials concerned.

Video Movies on National Reunification Produced
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 30 (KCNA) -- The Video Workshop "By Our Nation Itself" of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea has produced video movies including "June 15 for Reunification" and "Songs Eulogizing the Idea of 'By Our Nation Itself'" (five years seen through songs).
 The "June 15 for Reunification" deals with functions of the grand festival for national reunification marking the fifth anniversary of the June 15 north-south joint declaration held in Pyongyang from June 14 to 17, Juche 94 (2005). &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It impressively shows scenes of colorful events of the festival including a grand national march for independence, peace and reunification and an opening ceremony of the festival. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Seen in the movie are scenes showing leader Kim Jong Il receiving a special envoy of the south side President, those related with the north-south summit and the widow of Rev. Mun Ik Hwan respectively. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It stresses that the festival fully demonstrated to the whole world the will of all the Korean people to bring about the new era for the independent reunification with their concerted efforts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Edited in the movie "Songs Eulogizing the Idea of 'By Our Nation Itself'" are some of the songs on the theme of national reunification the Korean people in the north and the south have loudly sung over the last five years after the publication of the joint declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It gives, along with scenes of functions, such songs as "Reunification Coming under the Banner of June 15", "Reunification by Our Nation Itself", "National Cooperation Is Best" and "Rooter's Song for Reunification" that the Koreans from the north, south and overseas sang at pro-reunification rallies as songs calling for reunification in the June 15 era. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Seen in the movie are scenes showing broad sections of the south Korean people singing the songs "Glad to See You", "Arirang of National Reunification", "Korea Is One" and "See You Again". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The video films reflecting optimism for reunification powerfully inspire the fellow countrymen in the efforts to achieve the reunification of the country without fail by thoroughly implementing the joint declaration with the united strength of the nation.
